\chapter{Extending the Candle Kernel}\label{chap:extending-kernel}

In this chapter we will explain the implementation of the module system for Candle, and how it fits into the existing sources. Ultimately, the goal of the section is to justify and explain the implementation. Discussion on the verification of the system is not mentioned until Chapter \ref{chap:proving-soundness}. 

We begin with a high-level explanation of the design goals to achieve a usable system, before moving onto the technical aspects of the implementation. 

\section{Design goals for the usability of the system}

Before any implementation details of the system can be discussed, it is clear that some preliminary discussion on design goals is needed. We have described what a module system entails for the purposes of this project; this subsection will introduce what that should end up looking like--in high level--to motivate the following content. At the end of this section, we revisit the monoid example from the introduction to show how our extended system would handle it, and to show how it fits into our design goals. We propose as these design goals that the system should be able to do the following:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Support reusable abstraction:} The system should allow users to define parameterised collections of theorems and later instantiate them on concrete types and constants. This enables proof reuse over common algebraic structures, reducing repeated proofs.
    \item \textbf{Minimal work to apply a module:} The purpose of the system is to make the user's life easier; once a module has been written, it should be as simple as possible to instantiate it and start using its transported theorems on the concrete type.
    \item \textbf{Integrate into existing theories:} HOL4 is already in heavy use. The system should be able to be used to enrich existing theories.
\end{itemize}

\section{The Candle backend}

We now take a break from discussing our original work to explain the key parts of the Candle sources that we must modify to implement our system. 

\subsection{Project structure}

A subset of the project structure that we are interested in is shown in Figure \ref{fig:candle-sources}. This shows the split between syntax and semantics that we described in Chapter \ref{chap:background}. 
